Cars4U Project: Vanika Hans¶

Section 1: Project Background and Objectives¶

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

The objectives of this investigation are to assist Cars4U in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing by coming up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars. This will be done by:

  1. Visualizing the dataset and comprehending the data
  2. Building a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars
  3. Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business. For example, the business will not set pricing below the market price.

Concepts to Cover¶

  1. Overview of the data
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis
  3. Data Preparation
  4. Choose Model, Train and Evaluate
  5. Conclusion
  6. Forward Feature Selection

Section 2: Data Dictionary/Overview¶

Before diving in, here is of the dataset:

Attribute Description
S.No. Serial Number
Name Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name
Location The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase Cities
Year Manufacturing year of the car
Kilometers_driven The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM.
Fuel_Type The type of fuel used by the car. (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
Transmission The type of transmission used by the car. (Automatic / Manual)
Owner Type of ownership
Mileage The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
Engine The displacement volume of the engine in CC.
Power The maximum power of the engine in bhp.
Seats Seats : The number of seats in the car.
New_Price The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs.(1 Lakh = 100, 000)
Price The price of the used car in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100, 000)

def simplify_name(fn_input):
    """Strips off specific model name from name, ie Hyundai Sonata will become just Hyundai."""
    if isinstance(fn_input, str):
        splt = fn_input.split(" ")
        return str(splt[0])
    else:
        return np.nan

df['Name_Simplified'] = df['Name']
df['Name_Simplified'] = df['Name_Simplified'].apply(simplify_name)

Extra step: Since the majority of units are in kmpl, let us convert the km/kg also to kmpl, and then drop the unit. This way, all the numbers are in the same unit before we drop the unit and just leave the number.¶

In [15]:
def convert_mileage_units(fn_input):
    """Returns the units of the function input from df."""
    substring = "kg"
    if isinstance(fn_input, str):
        splt = fn_input.split(" ")
        if substring in splt[1]:
            splt[1]="kmpl"
            dummy_string = " ".join(splt)
            fn_input=str(dummy_string)
            fn_input = ''.join(fn_input)
            return fn_input
        else:
            fn_input = ''.join(fn_input)
            return fn_input
    else:
        return np.nan
    
df['Mileage_Units'] = df['Mileage'].apply(convert_mileage_units)

def drop_units(fn_input):
    """Drops units"""
    
    substring = "null"
        
    if isinstance(fn_input, str):
        if substring in fn_input: #ex/ if the word "null bhp" shows up
            fn_input = 0
            return float(fn_input)
        else:
            splt = fn_input.split(" ")
            fn_input = splt[0]
            return(float(fn_input))
    else:
        return np.nan

df['Mileage_Units'] = df['Mileage'].apply(drop_units)

def convert_cr_to_lakh(fn_input):
    """Converts cr to lakh, outputs string unit"""
    substring = "Cr"
    if isinstance(fn_input, str):
        splt = fn_input.split(" ")
        if substring in splt[1]:
            print("Before Conversion: ",fn_input)
            dummy = float(splt[0]) * 100
            splt[0]=str(dummy)
            splt[1]="Lakh"
            dummy_string = " ".join(splt)
            fn_input=str(dummy_string)
            fn_input = ''.join(fn_input)
            print("After Conversion: ",fn_input)
            return fn_input
        else:
            fn_input = ''.join(fn_input)
            return fn_input
    else:
        return np.nan
    
df['New_Price_Converted'] = df['New_Price'].apply(convert_cr_to_lakh)

# While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency 
# and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(7,7), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='green', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

Section 9: Model-Building Prep¶

Outlier Handling¶

Lets treat outliers by flooring and capping.¶

In [123]:
def treat_outliers(df,col):
    '''
    treats outliers in a variable
    col: str, name of the numerical variable
    df: data frame
    col: name of the column
    '''
    Q1=df[col].quantile(0.25) # 25th quantile
    Q3=df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR=Q3-Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5*IQR 
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker) # all the values samller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned value of Lower_whisker 
                                                            # and all the values above upper_whishker will be assigned value of upper_Whisker 
    return df

def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    '''
    treat outlier in all numerical variables
    col_list: list of numerical variables
    df: data frame
    '''
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df,c)
        
    return df
In [124]:
numerical_col = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
df = treat_outliers_all(df,numerical_col)

In [140]:
# MAPE
def mape(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)) / targets) * 100

# Adjusted R^2
def adj_r2(ind_vars, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = ind_vars.shape[0]
    k = ind_vars.shape[1]
    return 1-((1-r2)*(n-1)/(n-k-1))

# Model performance check
def model_perf(model, inp, out):

    y_pred = model.predict(inp)
    y_act = out.values

    return pd.DataFrame({
                "MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_act, y_pred),
                "MAPE": mape(y_act, y_pred),
                "RMSE": np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_act, y_pred)),
                "R^2": r2_score(y_act, y_pred),
                "Adjusted R^2": adj_r2(inp, y_act, y_pred)
           }, index=[0])

Section 11: Conclusion¶

From this investigation, the following was confirmed:

  1. Power and Price have a high positive correlation. Higher power has a higher price.
  2. Engine and Price also have a high positive correlation. Higher Engine CC has a higher price.
  3. New car prices are sold at various prices that have a high positive correlation to used car prices. Interestingly, many new cars Luxury brands like Lamborghini are priced at 11.415 Lakhs. So long as the used car prices are slightly lower than this, that should be a good guidline for pricing.
  4. In used cars, Lamborghini is priced the most expensive, followed Bentley, Porche, Land, and Jaguar clearly follow after.
  5. Cars in Coimbatore, Bangalore, and Kochi are priced highest for used cars, wheras newer cars priced almost relatively the same when purchased in Coimatore, Bangalore, and Kochi.
  6. For used cars, LPG is priced lowest, and Diesel/Electric are priced highest for used cars. In the case of new cars, while CNG, Petrol, and LPG cars are still cheaper than Diesel and Electric cars, there isn't as huge of difference in pricing.
  7. Used automated cars are priced much higher than manual cars. Interestingly, used automatic cars are priced higher than used automatic cars.
  8. The cost for used cars decreases as the number of owners on the car increases. The same pattern is there for new cars, just not as dramatic of a decrease.

In terms of the model fitting, both the $R^2$ and RMSSE show that the model fitted is good, and that there is no overfitting. In addition, the training and testing RMSE are 1.86 and 1.92 respectively, and both scores are comparable. Additinally, the $R^2$ is 88.99%, meaning that ~88.99% of total variation in the dataset. So, overall the model is very satisfactory.
